{
  "doc_id": "40948",
  "text": "In studying Earth's changing climate, it is often difficult or impossible to decipher a signal from the noise of weather and the climate system's inherent chaotic and cyclic nature. It is therefore sometimes preferable to focus climate studies on the tropical regions, which are less affected by traveling synoptic patterns than are the higher latitudes, and more directly reflect the mean state of the climate. This is due, in part, to generally homogeneous thermal conditions that exist in the tropics because of the lack of influence of the Coriolis effect [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Additionally, much of the climatic activity that greatly affects humans, such as the El Nin˜o-Southern Oscillation (ENSO), the Inter-Tropical Convergence Zone (ITCZ), and the Asian monsoon, are centered in the tropics [CITATION_3] . Tropical glaciers are exceptional indicators of environmental changes, including changes in the annual mean state of the climate, and the effects of these changes on natural systems [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] .",
